Building a shiny application step by step

Step 1 :

Build an application, which will ask the user to enter a first name and will display the evolution of its popularity curve

To help you you can start from the template template_app1.R

Step 2 :

Improve the previous application by adding a sentence that indicates the total number of births for the selected first name

You can use the glue::glue function to build this sentence

Step 3 :

Replace the free text box with a drop-down menu offering to choose from an existing first name

Step 4 :

Add a drop-down menu proposing to modify the color of the graph plot You can use palette() to create a color vector. You may need to edit the draw_a_name function by adding a colorparameter.

Step 5 :

Using a multiple slider input, ask the user to specify a period for which to draw the graph ( you can use ggplot2::xlim() or ggplot2::coord_cartesian(xlim=)but these 2 functions dont do exactly the same thing ). (If you want you can adjust the sentence reated at step 2)

Step 6 :

Add under the graph the table of births by year for the selected name. Remember to use reactive to filter on first name only once

Step 7

Two checkboxes (girls/boys) must be added to allow to filter (or not) on sex . (without using reactive it could be tricky)

Step 8

Changing the color of the graph must not regenerate the graph (it will only be regenerated if the slider or name is changed)

Step 9 :

Now only one press of a button should allow you to modify the graph.

Step 10:

Although only the button regenerates the graph, set up a log system that indicates that the user is modifying something (by displaying something in the console for example)

Optimisation

Are you sure you have used optimal approaches in all your previous answers? Make sure, for example, that you do not redo calculations for nothing when you simply change a color -> you have to use as many reactive as necessary, cut your code into small pieces to perform a calculation only when it is really necessary.

Does your application take time to display? Isnt this because you ask the UI part to do a costly calculation (to return all possible names, especially if you sort the names in alphabetical order). Try to initialize the selectInput choices to NULL instead and then edit it with an updateSelectInput. The user experience will be greatly improved

Does your application display, even temporarily, error messages in red on the UI side? If so, look at how the req, validate or need functions can help you.

Step 11:

Edit the IU by adding a tabPanel on it (one tab for graph, one other for the table), Feel free to make it a little prettier.

Step 12:

Create a ShinyModule of your app. You can easily then recall this piece of app in another application

Step 13:

Create an R package containing your app.

The most ambitious approach is here : https://rtask.thinkr.fr/blog/our-shiny-template-to-design-a-prod-ready-app/

But the quick way is to follow the first 2 steps of this article https://translate.google.fr/translate?hl=fr&sl=auto&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fthinkr.fr%2Fdockeriser-application-shiny%2F (you dont have to deal with docker here, juste to create an R package)
